An identifier’sscopedetermines where the identifier can be seen and used within the source code. When an identifier can be seen and used, we say it isin scope. When an identifier can not be seen, we can not use it, and we say it isout of scope. Scope is a compile-time property, and trying to use an identifier when it is not in scope will result in a compile error.The identifier of a local variable has local scope. An identifier withlocal scope(technically calledblock scope) is usable from the point of definition to the end of the innermost pair of curly braces containing the identifier (or for function parameters, at the end of the function). This ensures local variables cannot be used before the point of definition (even if the compiler opts to create them before then) or after they are destroyed. Local variables defined in one function are also not in scope in other functions that are called.Here’s a program demonstrating the scope of a variable namedx:#include <iostream>

